{[show S]Responder holds five-four in the majors with game-going values opposite a 1NT opening. How should the partnership look for a major fit, and which hand should end up declaring?
[BID 1N] ⟦You have a balanced 15 to 17, so open 1NT and let partner take charge of finding the right strain.⟧ Your partner starts with Stayman, asking whether opener holds a four-card major. With five-four in the majors and enough for game, this is the first step of the Smolen route.
[BID 2D] ⟦2\D denies a four-card major. You have no major to show, so steer toward responder's next bid.⟧ The jump to 3\S is Smolen: it shows four spades and therefore five hearts. Your partner points opener at the five-card heart suit and asks for support.
[BID 4H] ⟦With three-card heart support, you complete the picture by bidding game in the implied five-card suit. 4\H puts the strong hand on lead from the right side.⟧
[show NS]North's five hearts and four spades opposite South's balanced 15 found the eight-card heart fit through Smolen. Because South described the 1NT range and North jumped to show the five-three major, the partnership reached 4\H with the opening lead coming up to the strong hand.}
